{{Infobox website | name = Louder Than War | logo = Louder Than War Logo.png | logo_size = 250px | logo_alt = Louder Than War logo | logo_caption = Louder Than War logo | screenshot = <!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Louder Than War homepage.png|300px]] --> | collapsible = | collapsetext = | background = | screenshot_size = | screenshot_alt = Louder Than War homepage | caption = | url = {{URL|www.louderthanwar.com}} | commercial = | type = Music, news and media | registration = | language = English | num_users = | content_license = | programming_language = | owner = | creator = [[John Robb (musician)|John Robb]] | editor = Phil Newall | launch_date = 2010 | revenue = | alexa = | ip = | current_status = | footnotes = }}
'''''Louder Than War''''' is a music and culture website and magazine focusing on mainly alternative arts news, reviews, and features. The site is an editorially independent publication that was started by journalist [[John Robb (musician)|John Robb]] in 2010 and is now run by a team of other journalists with a worldwide team of freelancers. There has been a print edition since 2015
The site is built around live reviews, album reviews and exclusive in-depth interviews with many key musicians including [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]], [[Kurt Cobain]], [[John Lydon]], [[Peter Hook]], [[The Stranglers]], [[The Charlatans (UK band)|The Charlatans]], [[The Damned (band)|The Damned]] and [[Happy Mondays|The Happy Mondays]]. In 2012, ''Louder Than War'' launched a record label<ref>{{Cite news|title = Louder Than War Launches Label |url = http://thequietus.com/articles/08372-louder-than-war-record-label/|work = The Quietus|accessdate = 15 January 2016|language = en-GB}}</ref> to promote and champion lesser known bands and artists.
The website broke the story of [[The Stone Roses]]' reformation<ref>{{Cite news|title = Stone Roses reformation is definite, and new album as well...|url = http://louderthanwar.com/stone-roses-reformation-definite-and-new-album-as-well/|work = Louder Than War|accessdate = 15 January 2016|language = en-GB}}</ref> and was a supporter of the "Justice Tonight for the 96" [[Hillsborough disaster|Hillsborough]] tour.
John Robb is also a member of the English punk rock bands [[The Membranes]] and [[Goldblade]].
==History== In its first year, in November 2011, Robb was voted to win the UK Association of Independent Music "Indie Champion" award.<ref>{{Cite web|title=AIM Independent Music Awards : 2011&nbsp;– The Association of Independent Music |url=http://www.musicindie.com/awards/awards2011 |website=www.musicindie.com |accessdate=13 September 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913160612/http://www.musicindie.com/awards/awards2011 |archivedate=13 September 2015 |df= }}</ref>
As part of the creation of the website, the ''Louder Than War'' team wrote their own manifesto,<ref>{{Cite news|title = Manifesto |url = http://louderthanwar.com/about-us/|work = Louder than War|accessdate = 15 January 2016|language = en-GB}}</ref> which would guide their editorial content.
In 2014 Louder Than War created the record label '''Louder Than War Records''' to act as a platform for bands and artists to reach a wider audience; the first release being Evil Blizzard 'The Dangers Remixes', a 300 copy CD only release without a catalogue number, each being hand numbered; the 8 track releases being a remix of the at that point still to be released Evil Blizzard debut 'The Dangers of Evil Blizzard' (LOUD001). The label has since gone on to release material by King Champion Sounds, Faerground Accidents, The Nightingales, Super Besses, Get Your Gun, and The Membranes.
In August 2015, ''Louder Than War'' announced they were also creating a print/magazine version of the website.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Louder Than War announces launch of print/magazine version of website |url = http://louderthanwar.com/louder-than-war-announces-launch-of-printmagazine-version-of-website/|work = Louder than War|accessdate = 15 January 2016|language = en-GB}}</ref> The first issue of ''Louder Than War'' magazine was published by Big Cheese Publishing Ltd in autumn 2015 and followed a similar style and format to the website.
In September 2015, Sarah Lay became Editor with John Robb becoming Editor-in-Chief of the online and offline publications.
In July 2017 Lay left. The website continues to be run by Robb and Associate Editor Phil Newall and a team of other section editors, journalists and contributors worldwide.
